import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class Solution {
    public List<Integer> length_of_cycle(int n, int[][] queries) {
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList();
        for (int[] query : queries) {
            int depth_A = 0, depth_B = 0, A = query[0], B = query[1];
            while (A != B) {
                if (A < B) {
                    int tmp = A;
                    A = B;
                    B = tmp;
                }
                A >>= 1;
                depth_A++;
            }
            result.add(depth_A + depth_B);
        }
        return result;
    }
} 
```

    The algorithm is based on tree traversal. For each query `[A, B]`, we keep track of the depth of nodes `A` and `B`. We traverse the tree by moving both nodes up (dividing by 2) until they become equal.

In each iteration, if `A < B`, we swap `A` and `B`. Then, we divide `A` by 2 and increment the depth of node `A`. This continues until nodes `A` and `B` become the same.

After the loop, the length of the cycle is the sum of the depths of both nodes.

This algorithm doesn't need to add and remove edges, as finding the nodes' depths gives us the cycle length directly.
